description:
Ballechin – Highland Single Malt Scotch Whisky 
 Situated in the picturesque countryside of the Scottish Highlands, the Ballechin Distillery stands as a testament to the peat whisky’s enduring heritage. As part of the Edradour Distillery, one of Scotland’s smallest and most traditional distilleries, Ballechin breathes new life into the ancient art of peat whisky production. 
 Ballechin’s journey began as a tribute to a long-lost distillery of the same name, known for its heavily peated malt. Today, Ballechin Distillery honours this heritage by creating a range of whiskies that are a bold exploration of peat, showcasing the rich and smoky flavours that are synonymous with Scotland’s whisky history.

title: Salon Champagne
cate_info_ai: [{"catId":609342,"catPath":"Food and beverage => Alcoholic Beverages => Sparkling Wines and Cider => Champagnes","catUrl":"https://vtyler.alibaba.com/vtyler/index.htm?categoryId=609342"}]
keyword_ai: {"keywords":{"3":"Le Mesnil-sur-Oger Champagne","1":"Champagne Salon","2":"Chardonnay Champagne"},"keywords_english":{"3":"Le Mesnil-sur-Oger Champagne","1":"Salon Champagne","2":"Chardonnay Champagne"}}
description: The Champagne Salon was born in 1901 by Aimé Salon, who wanted a champagne to his liking, for his own consumption and that of his friends. This champagne comes from a single grape variety, Chardonnay, from a single vineyard, Le Mesnil-sur-Oger, and from a single vintage! It is produced without any blend and without malolactic fermentation in order to preserve a strong acidity and promote ageing. Folgers Coffee is a storied American brand that has been a staple in households since the mid-19th century. Known for its rich flavor and iconic jingle, “The Best Part of Wakin’ Up is Folgers in Your Cup,” the brand has evolved over the years while maintaining its commitment to quality and community. 
 Founded in 1850 in San Francisco by James A. Folger, the company began as the Pioneer Steam Coffee and Spice Mills. James Folger, at just 14 years old, started working at the mill and eventually became a full partner. In 1865, he bought out the other partners and renamed the company J.A. Folger & Co. The brand gained national recognition in the early 20th century, thanks in part to salesman Frank P. Atha, who expanded its reach beyond California. In 1963, Procter & Gamble acquired Folgers, and later, in 2008, The J.M. Smucker Company purchased the brand, where it continues to thrive today.
